 is an optimization algorithm used to find the local minimum of a function. It works by iteratively moving towards the direction of steepest descent as defined by the negative of the gradient (or approximate gradient) of the function. This process continues until convergence, typically measured by a predefined stopping criterion such as a maximum number of iterations or a threshold on the change in the objective function value. The goal is to minimize the cost function, which could represent errors in regression problems, loss functions in classification tasks, or energy landscapes in machine learning models.", "cited_chunk_ids": [], "refused": false, "generation_latency_seconds": 6.452336832997389}
